narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments:
I learnt important aspects of calculus and deepened my understanding of it. After taking this class, I feel way more comfortable with calculus, which I will need for my major. I think, overall, it provided me with solid foundations to continue with mathematics classes.
Overall, it was quite a good interaction to calculus.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Improvements: more practice problems in class; spend more time on the challenging material near the end of the semester which felt rushed and less on the easy material at the start; clearer explanations of the content; improve the homework grading system - there were usually very few comments by graders so it was unclear why you were losing marks

The most important weakness was homework workload. The amount of homework was very big, and almost impossible to complete within a week. The problem sets were very long and tedious, very hard to grasp even after attending lectures. The worse aspect of this class were undoubtedly the very hard, tedious, time-consuming and impossible to complete problems sets. Ironically, the worst component of my grade were the problem sets. The exercises there were the hardest, they were very hard and tedious and they did not even appear in worksheets we did in class, in exams, or in the lectures. And the worst part of it all: they didnt even provide us with solutions to the problems sets, they just gave vague feedback on our mistakes! Also, the Ximeras were way too many as well!

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, if you need it for a major. No if you need a QR or want to do it for fun - theres better courses.
I would, as I said, it was an overall good class, and a very good introduction to calculus.
